Today, weâ€™re celebrating #BlackHerstoryMonth by celebrating the life and legacy of our very own Dr. Dorothy Height. Known as the â€œgodmother of the civil rights movement,â€ she dedicated her life to the intersectional mission of racial and gender equality and inspired other well-known civil rights leaders, including Martin Luther King, Jr. Dr. Height was one of the nationâ€™s most steadfast civil rights activists, whose intersectional activism as our first Director of Racial Justice led to YWCAâ€™s One Imperative to #EliminateRacism, wherever it exists, by any means necessary. #BHM2022

Toni Morrison is one of the most celebrated authors in the world with her catalogue of books including, â€œThe Bluest Eye,â€ â€œSong of Solomon,â€ and â€œHome.â€ Her work often grappled with issues of race, class, and gender equity, always with a focus on African American culture. During her career, Toni Morrison won MANY prestigious awards including the Pulitzer Price, the presidential Medal of Freedom, and she was the first Black woman to be awarded the Nobel Prize in literature. No one could write on the experience of Black American life quite like her, and no one has since. Through her work at Random House publishing, she was also able to edit works and support other incredible Black writers such as Toni Cade Bambara, Gayl Jones, and Angela Davis. Toni Morrison not only dedicated her work to sharing #BlackStories, but her dedication to making space for other Black women and authors to write about our history through the lenses of magical realism and historical fiction was unprecedented. The far-reaching impacts of her work cannot be understated, and her legacy is truly #legendary. #BlackHerstoryMonth

Today on The Truman Charities Podcast with Jamie Truman: Manizha and her family fled Afghanistan during the Cold War in the 1980's when she was only 5 years old. Being a refugee herself, she knows all too well what these newly arrived families have endured and the obstacles that they may face being in a completely new environment. Manizha leads with compassion and wants to empower refugees, particularly the women and children, by example. She began volunteering with IROC as a result of her deep desire to support and empower those in need. Manizha is a mother of four beautiful children and her husband served in the US Army Special Forces. Manizha earned her Associates in Science from Farmingdale State College, NY. She is also a successful franchisee and most recently accepted a position as a Family Service Manager at Homes Not Borders. Listen to this uplifting Truman Charities episode with Manizha Azizi about her selfless help to aid refugees through Homes Not Borders. Here is what to expect on this weekâ€™s show: - Some of the challenges Manizha faced as a refugee. - The current crisis that is going on in Afghanistan. - The tools her organization is providing these refugee families and how they will help them succeed. - The values of Homes Not Borders. Today on For Lawyers Only: #PracticingWithPurpose with Cindy Watson: Tahmina Watson is an immigration attorney and founder of Watson Immigration Law in Seattle, Washington. She has helped hundreds of individuals and American businesses navigate the complexities of US immigration laws to unite loved ones and talent. Tahmina is a passionate advocate for immigration reform. With over 15 years of experience as a practitioner and business owner, and as an immigrant from the UK to the US with Bangladeshi heritage, she is able to help her clients with empathy and excellence. She regularly advises policymakers and think tanks. Tahmina is the host of the podcast Tahmina Talks Immigration. She is a regular speaker at immigration and industry conferences. She has been blogging since 2008 and her articles have been published in The Seattle Times, Above the Law, Geekwire, Puget Sound Business Journal, Scary Mommy, Yes! Magazine and more. She has been quoted and featured in numerous media outlets including CNN, Forbes, Bloomberg, to name a few. A recipient of several awards, Tahmina was named as one of the 2020 Puget Sound Business Journal Women of Influence. In this episode, we discuss: -The reasons why Tahima stayed away from the thing that was pulling her in at the beginning of her career in the US: immigration. - What immigration taught her about people, and why helping people is the backbone of her practice. -Why the privilege of sharing good news matters. -How working in the 2016 election, and losing, gave her the drive to start an immigration committee in her community to help those around her. -The importance of knowing what calls you to your passion. We are happy to announce the theme of the NLPA2022 annual Conferencia is 'Dynamic Latinx Healthcare: Integrative wellness through the lens of culture and community. This year we proudly celebrate NLPA's 20th anniversary of proactively creating supportive professional spaces that advance psychological education and training focused on improving the well-being of Latinx communities. Our Conferencia's theme aims to showcase new research, clinical practices, and applied models that examine how integrative relationships in healthcare are essential to building community wellness. We welcome presentations on an array of issues related to integrative wellness, collaborative delivery models, recruitment and retention, training issues in medical settings, interdisciplinary collaboration and treatments, the intersection of psychology and medical comorbidities, holistic and alternative healing methods, and implementation of new policies and infrastructure that support psychological integration in healthcare settings. We strongly encourage the submission of proposals that highlight the AfroLatinx perspective and address health disparities across underrepresented groups within the Latinx community. Presentation formats requested this year include symposia, workshops, poster sessions, and round table discussion groups. We extend this special invitation to the interdisciplinary community which includes but is not limited to mental health professionals, people with lived experiences, physicians, educators, holistic healers, administrators, and community stakeholders.

Today (May 19) is National Asian and Pacific Islander HIV/AIDS Awareness Day (NAPIHAAD), an annual observance founded by the Banyan Tree Project. As we work to end the HIV epidemic, we must address the unique needs of Asian and Pacific Islander (API) communities. Central to ending HIV is fighting discrimination, including acts of anti-Asian harassment and violence throughout the pandemic. We cannot end the HIV epidemic without serving and supporting API communities, and that includes standing up against discrimination. Anti-violence and anti-discrimination work is also HIV prevention. Learn more in our latest blog post: https://www.amidacareny.org/aapi-heritage-month-celebrating-contributions-supporting-equity/ #NAPIHAAD #NAPIHAAD2022 #apimay19 #AAPI #StopAsianHate

Although HIV research is always advancing, there is a lack of research focusing on Asian and Pacific Islander (API) populations. Considering new HIV transmissions among API populations decreased by only 3% in New York since 2001 according to the CDC, there's also a need to increase access to HIV prevention and treatment resources. Next Thursday (May 19) for National Asian and Pacific Islander HIV/AIDS Awareness Day (NAPIHAAD), join us in calling for increased and improved resources and outreach to address HIV and its impact on API communities to end HIV. Dr. Isabella Abbott was an educator, phycologist, & ethnobotanist of Hawaiian & Chinese desecent. The first native Hawaiian woman to receive a PhD in science, she became a leading expert on Pacific marine algae. Fun Fact: She was credited with discovering over 200 species of seaweed, with several named after her, including the Rhodomelaceae family (red algae) genus of Abbottella. This earned her the nickname "First Lady of Limu."

Freddie Tavares is an American musician and inventor of Portuguese, Hawaiian, Chinese, English, Tahitian-Samoan heritage. He was best known for his role in designing the Fender Stratocaster and other Fender instruments and amplifiers. Fun Fact: The signature steel guitar swoop at the beginning of every Warner Bros. Looney Tunes theatrical short was played by Tavares.

MKJF will match every dollar raised by you! Please donate today! 3 DAYS LEFT TO HAVE YOUR DONATION MATCHED DOLLAR FOR DOLLAR! Dear Friends, As the days turn into weeks with the Russian invasion we salute the heroic and tireless efforts of the valiant professionals at The Jewish Agency for Israel, JDC, and World ORT and other organizations who are acting as the long arm of our Federations delivering critical assistance to the Jewish community in its hour of need. JFNA's first Fly-In to the Polish-Ukrainian border just wrapped up; it was an unforgettable experience for the first thirty Federation leaders who participated this week. After flying to Warsaw and being briefed by Polish Jewish leaders, we witnessed thousands of refugees crossing into Poland and being taken care of by our partners, the Jewish Agency and JDC, as well as by the many other relief agencies from around the world that have converged in eastern Poland. You can view brief clips of participants reflecting about the trip here. Another Fly-In is set for next week, and two additional ones are planned for early April. For the latest information on the emergency response activities of JDC and the Jewish Agency read todayâ€™s Ukraine Crisis update. It is also being widely reported today that Prime Minister Bennett has been the â€œprimary international negotiatorâ€ in the ongoing peace talks between Russia and Ukraine. For more, see todayâ€™s Times of Israel article. We pray that these efforts bear fruit in the very near future. In an inspiring show of generosity our Federations intensive fundraising efforts to meet the immediate needs of the crisis continue; Federations have collectively raised more than $27 million since the crisis began three weeks ago. Thank you for all that you are doing and please keep the momentum going! The Mid-Kansas Jewish Federation will match every dollar raised from our community, including dollars that have already been donated by YOU. Donations to be matched will need to arrive in our office by Monday, March 21, 2022. 3 DAYS LEFT TO MATCH YOUR DONATION! JFNA has appointed a Ukraine Allocations Subcommittee of the Israel and Overseas Committee to allocate funds and get money moving to the field now. David Brown from Chicago, former Chair of the I&O Committee and incoming Vice Chair of JFNA, will lead this work. The Subcommittee will meet later today and we will update you tomorrow on the first round of approved allocations. An emergency campaign is underwayâ€“click here to make your donation, mail or drop off a check to the MKJF at 1850 N. Woodlawn, Wichita, Kansas 67208. Please note that is is for the UKRAINE. Our partners will utilize this support in a variety of ways, including: Â· Maintaining critical welfare services Â· Emergency aliyah and community security Â· Temporary housing for those in transit Â· Stockpiling goods Â· Satellite phones to ensure communication Â· Ensuring staff at Jewish school are safe and prepared to respond Â· Medical staff supports With your support, we are ready to help. We also will closely follow all developments and will update you with any pertinent information. Our office has reached out to some in the community to check if they know anyone that needs assistance. If you know of someone in need, please contact our office. We are all part of Kehilat Yisrael. Whenever and wherever one Jew is threatened, we are all responsible to come to their aid. While we pray for peace, we also work to help all those in danger. Sincerely, Seth Merrell MKJF Board President Julie Fruhauf MKJF Director

Chris Dickerson, who rose from a childhood in the Jim Crow-era South to become one of the worldâ€™s greatest bodybuilders, breaking barriers as the first Black Mr. America and the first openly gay Mr. Olympia. Throughout his lengthy career, Dickerson amassed 50 titles, including wins at International Federation of Bodybuilding and Fitness Grand Prix competitions in multiple states, the Post said. While he refrained from speaking about his personal life during his career, Dickerson often stood by the sport breaking down misconceptions about it. "Some people like flashy cars, some like flashy hairdos; we like healthy bodies," said Dickerson once per the Post. "Everybody's got their own thing, and ours is no funnier than anybody else."

Please join Myriad Health + Fitness in celebrating Black History Month throughout February. The 2022 theme is Black Health and Wellness, acknowledging the legacy of not only Black scholars and medical practitioners, but also considers activities, rituals and initiatives Black communities have done to be well. Black Health and Wellness not only includes oneâ€™s physical body, but also oneâ€™s emotional and mental health. Throughout the month, Myriad Health + Fitness will be highlighting important figures who have paved the way in the health and wellness realm. We will share stories of the role yoga has played in the lives of historical Black figures, how Crossfit is working to be more inclusive and other resources to help you support Black practitioners and initiatives.

It's our last Wild Winter Wednesday and our final program of the season will be a Mill Flour Bake Off! All entries must use de Immigrant ground flour. To get an entry form, print off the photo attached here or email fulton.tourism@cityoffulton.us . Attendees will judge the best tasting entries and each of the Bake Off entries will be available for sale by donation on a first come, first bid basis. In conjunction with the Bake Off we will be displaying local student art work. This is a perfect ending to our WWW series, and we want you to be part of it! The doors open at 9:00 a.m. for coffee, tea, and mill treats. The program begins about 9:20. The building is disability accessible, and the program is funded through a grant from the D.S. Flikkema Foundation and a donation from Nelson Corp. The programs are free and open to the public. There is no charge but donations are accepted. Hope to see you there! #ReasonsToVisit #thingstodo #windmillsofinstagram #windmillculturalcenter #visitfulton #bakeoff #bakesale
